<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>DDB0172</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Detention Action – Written evidence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Detention Action’s evidence concerns exclusively Clause 40 of the Bill.  The clause would remove access to accommodation and support under Section 4.1 from migrants released from detention on either temporary admission or high court bail.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">This power is a live provision that is in use.  As such, it falls outside of the long title of the Bill.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Sections 4.1.a and 4.1.b of the Immigration and Asylum Act 1999 contain powers that are not in general use for the vast majority of migrants on temporary admission, to whom they might be used to provide accommodation.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">However, these powers are regularly used to enable the release from detention of small numbers of migrants at risk of unlawful detention.  Indeed, the circumstances in which the powers are used are generally of high urgency, in order to avoid unlawful detention and / or severe harm to the individual.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Detention Action has supported a small but significant number of individuals who have been released to Section 4 support in these circumstances.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> These cases have been in the course of unlawful detention litigation in the High Court, where either the Home Office has agreed to release or release has been ordered by the High Court.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> In many cases further detention will be unlawful, sometimes because of extreme health or mental health issues exacerbated by detention.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Most of these detainees are not eligible for support under Section 4.2 of the Act. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The power to release under S4.1.b is vital both for the rights of these individuals and for the operation of immigration control.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> The Home Office will usually wish to know the address at which the released migrants will be living, for example in order to implement electronic monitoring of an ex-offender.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> In addition, the High Court routinely requires a designated address and electronic monitoring when releasing migrants after finding their detention to have been unlawful.  The removal of the power to provide support under Section 4.1(a) and (b) of the Act would prevent the Home Office from carrying out such rulings of the High Court.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">It would also force highly vulnerable individuals into permanent destitution, since release in the context of unlawful detention litigation generally signifies that return to country of origin will not be possible for the foreseeable future.  This would risk incurring breaches of Articles 3 and 8 of the European Convention on Human Rights.  Individuals affected would in the majority of cases be from groups with protected characteristics, including race and disability.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The proposal to delete these clauses is at best highly controversial.  It would bring severe practical, policy and rights impacts on the treatment of highly vulnerable individuals.  It is entirely unsuitable for inclusion in the Deregulation Bill, and should be deleted.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Case studies:</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">A was released on temporary admission to support under Section 4.1 in August 2012.  He held in immigration detention from December 2008 until that date.  He had a single criminal conviction for use of a false instrument.  He suffered from severe psychotic symptoms, necessitating the involvement of the Official Solicitor as he was not able to act in his own interests.  He was frequently highly distressed, and made multiple suicide attempts.  In December 2011 the High Court ordered that the Home Office release him or lodge an urgent Acknowledgment of Service. None was lodged, and his release was ordered subject to the production of a care plan.  The care plan took eight months to finalise.  His solicitor applied for a Section 4 address, and he was released to suitable accommodation for his needs.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">B was released on temporary admission by the Home Office to a Section 4 address in October 2011, a few days after he sewed his mouth shut as a protest against his detention.  He had no travel documents and his country of origin rarely issued documentation, so removal appeared unlikely.  He had no criminal convictions.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">U was released on bail by the High Court to a Section 4 address in the course of unlawful detention litigation, after six months of detention.  He was a torture survivor with severe post-traumatic stress disorder.  He made several suicide attempts and hunger strikes in detention.  On one occasion he refused food and fluids for 12 days and came close to death, before he was hospitalised and put on a drip.    </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">About Detention Action</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Detention Action is a national charity established in 1993 that aims to change the way that migrants are treated by immigration detention policy in the UK.  Detention Action defends the rights and improves the welfare of people in detention by combining support for individuals with campaigning for policy change.  Detention Action works primarily in </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Harmondsworth</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Colnbrook</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> Immigration Removal Centres, near Heathrow Airport in London.  All primary evidence is taken from our casework.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>